<section xml:id="lesson-06">
  <title>Lesson 6 - Inverse Functions
  </title>

  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li>Draw the inverse of a function from its graph.</li>
      <li>Find the inverse of a function algebraically.</li>
      <li>Identify restrictions required for a function to have an inverse.</li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <subsection xml:id="l6-draw-inverses">
    <title>Drawing Inverses from Graphs</title>

    <p>Draw the inverse of each function shown below.</p>

      <exercise xml:id="l6-ex1">
        <statement>
          <figure xml:id="l6-inv-graph-1">
            <caption>Graph of a function to be reflected across the line <m>y = x</m>.</caption>
            <image source="../figures/drawinv1-review.png">
              <description><p>Graph of a function to be reflected across the line <m>y = x</m> in order to draw its inverse.</p></description>
            </image>
          </figure>

          <figure xml:id="l6-inv-graph-2">
            <caption>Second graph to reflect across the line <m>y = x</m>.</caption>
            <image source="../figures/drawinv2-review.png">
              <description><p>Second graph of a function to be reflected across the line <m>y = x</m> to obtain its inverse.</p></description>
            </image>
          </figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The inverse of each function is obtained by reflecting the graph
            across the line <m>y = x</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="l6-find-inverses">
    <title>Finding Inverses Algebraically</title>

      <exercise xml:id="l6-ex2">
        <statement>
          <p>Find the inverse of each function.</p>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li><m>f(x) = 3x - 1</m></li>
            <li><m>f(x) = \frac{2x + 1}{x - 3}</m></li>
            <li><m>f(x) = (x - 1)^2</m>, <m>x \le 1</m></li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Let <m>y = f(x)</m>, interchange <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>, and solve
            for <m>y</m>. Apply the given domain restriction where required.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
  </subsection>

</section>